Introduction: Business Problem ¶

Background¶

In and around big cities with many inhabitants and many commuters, such as Seattle, accidents happen year-round. Sometimes accidents are severe and roads are blocked completely to rescue the injured, but even accidents with only propriety damage can cause traffic jams. It would be beneficial to have some warning beforehand so some areas could be bypassed.

Problem¶

This study aims to investigate whether the severity of an accident can be predicted on the basis of historical data including location, weather condition, light condition, road condition and others using supervised machine leaning.

Interest¶

Possible interested parties for the data can be local rescue stations, which can plan the rescue forces for example on the basis of local and weather forecasts. Better planning can both reduce costs and save lives by having the right resources readily available.

Another interested party could be radio stations, which can offer their listeners a forecast, either on traffic radio or on an online platform. This may increase the radio stations’ income generated by advertisements due more listeners or clicks on a platform. Insurances can also have an interest in the data because they may be able to forecast costs based on the expected severity of an accident.

Data ¶

The city of Seattle provides data on collisions here, a detailed description of the data is available here. The data is updated every week.

Data Cleaning and Preparation¶

The data covers several years of information starting at 2004-01-01 until 2020-07-29 at the time data was retrieved. Overall the original data has forty columns and 221266 rows, the SEVERITYCODE represents the label to be predicted, thirty nine columns are possible features.

To clean the data, missing values in estimators weather, light condition and road condition were first filled with “Unknown” and subsequently deleted together with the unknown specification “Others” because the data set is biased in favor of minor accidents and most of the “unknown” features occurred in minor accidents.

df3['INCDATE'] = pd.to_datetime(df3['INCDATE'])
df3['DAYOFWEEK'] = df3['INCDATE'].dt.dayofweek
df3['WEEKEND'] = df3['DAYOFWEEK'].apply(lambda x: 1 if (x>4) else 0)
df3['MONTH']=pd.DatetimeIndex(df3['INCDATE']).month
df3['YEAR']=pd.DatetimeIndex(df3['INCDATE']).year

# Serveritycode vs Weather Condition

df_weathercond=df3[['WEATHER','SEVERITYCODE']]
df_weathercond['Total'] = df_weathercond.sum(axis=1)
data_to_plot_wea = df_weathercond.groupby(['WEATHER','SEVERITYCODE'], as_index=False).count()
data_to_plot_wea_1=data_to_plot_wea[data_to_plot_wea['SEVERITYCODE']=='1']
data_to_plot_wea_2=data_to_plot_wea[data_to_plot_wea['SEVERITYCODE']=='2']
data_to_plot_wea_1.rename(columns={'SERITYCODE':'Incident_1', 'Total':'Total_INC1'},inplace=True)
data_to_plot_wea_2.rename(columns={'SERITYCODE':'Incident_2', 'Total':'Total_INC2'},inplace=True)
data_to_plot_wea_1.set_index('WEATHER', inplace=True)
data_to_plot_wea_2.set_index('WEATHER', inplace=True)

plot_wea  = pd.concat([data_to_plot_wea_1, data_to_plot_wea_2], axis=1, join='inner')
In [51]:
plot_wea['Total_Weather']=plot_wea[['Total_INC1','Total_INC2']].sum(axis=1)
plot_wea['Per_Inc2']=plot_wea['Total_INC2']/plot_wea['Total_Weather']
plot_weather=plot_wea['Per_Inc2']*100

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

mean_acc = np.zeros((Ks-1))
std_acc = np.zeros((Ks-1))
ConfustionMx = []
for n in range(1,Ks):

    yhat=ltree.predict(X_test)

    std_acc[n-1]=np.std(yhat==y_test)/np.sqrt(yhat.shape[0])

C = np.power(10, np.linspace(-5,1,21))

mean_acc = np.zeros(len(C))
std_acc = np.zeros(len(C))

for n, c in enumerate(C):

    #Train Model and Predict
    LR = LogisticRegression(C=c, solver='liblinear').fit(X_train,y_train)
    yhat=LR.predict(X_test)
    mean_acc[n-1] = f1_score(y_test, yhat, average='weighted')
    std_acc[n-1]=np.std(yhat==y_test)/np.sqrt(yhat.shape[0])

Discussion¶

Regarding the performance metrics, the Decicion Tree is the model wich perfomed best with the highest values for Jaccard and F1-score, followed by the random forest classifier. Trying to deal with the imbalance of the data using SMOTE for training, results in lower values for Jaccard and F1-score. But comparing on the confusion matrix for RFC without SMOTE with the one with SMOTE we see a shift in the correct predicion of severe accidents from 44.55% to 52.89%. Using SMOTE with Logistic Regression does not have the same effect, the correct prediction of severe accidents even drops slightly from 22.8% to 22.31%. Best in preditcion of severe accidents is the specialized algorithm for imbalanced data, BRFC, with 60.69%.

Conclusion ¶

Predictions on the outcome of accidents using classification on historical data are possible, but due to the imbalanced nature of the data, better predictions on the minority class can only be obtained by using oversampling techniques like SMOTE or a specialized algorithm like Balanced Random Forest Classifier. In context of the problem at hand it is arguabably more important to correctly predict the severe accidents than to have a good prediction of the minor accidents using the other algorithms. Since some features for prediction are only known after the accident actually occurs (number of involved persons, vehicles or speeding) the prediction is a help to calculate future costs rather then to be used to forecast traffic or planning human recources in rescue stations. The dependency on time of occurrance of accidents was not regarded, this may be an interesting feature for future study.
